<br>
i've been multiplying haste by weapon delay, then deducting the number from the original weapon delay..<br>
<br>
using that formula with a 22% haste makes a 20 delay weapon 16 delay, which (rounded) makes an exact 22% delay reduction.. *but* i'm being told its completely wrong by a *shaman*.. so.. can someone correct me? (or him, mwah) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=glaydor>Glaydor</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.mustangworks.com/gatorstang23/alig.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 246<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(7/8/02 12:58:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1681.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: haste</span><hr size=1> its actually half of what it says.<br>
<br>
Take a FBSS of instance. It has a haste effect of 21%. In effect it is a 10.5% haste<br>
<br>
So say a jade mace is a 9/18 weapon. with 21% haste its actually would approximatly be a 9/16 weapon. 100% haste would make it a 9/9 weapon not a 9/0 weapon<br>
<br>
If I am wrong, someone correct me. But this is how it was explained to me <p>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=220310</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/udaleb123.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daleb123</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(7/8/02 5:58:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1681.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Haste </span><hr size=1> The debate on the proper way to measure haste has raged for years. The two leading methods are Delay Reduction, and Increase in # of Attacks/time. You must be careful of any haste claims you read, as it is meaningless without the knowledge of how the measurement was done. Most of the lists you'll find here are based on the Increase in Attacks/time. <br>
<br>
For example, the FBSS gives a 21% increase in attacks/time. You can convert this to a change in Delay by this formula: Hasted Delay = Old Delay/(1 + Haste%); this assumes that Haste% was calculated as increase in Attacks/time. My Goranga Spiked Club has a Delay of 23; if I were to equip an FBSS, the Delay would become 23/1.21 = 19; note that this is approximately a 17% Delay Reduction. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=tarrask>Tarrask</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Monk-in-Training</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(7/9/02 9:17:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1681.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Haste </span><hr size=1> The example Daleb just gave is correct, and possibly the simplest explanation of the normal expression of haste I have seen - nice one. <p>Tarrask, 51st Swifttail of Saryrn
<BR>
<BR>
